@startuml
title WebRTC Signaling Flow Diagram

participant "User_App" as UserApp #LightBlue
participant "WebRTC_GW" as Gateway #White
database SkyWay_Server #Skyblue
actor Target_Peer #YellowGreen

== Peer Creation ==
UserApp ->> Gateway : POST /peers\n{\n  key: \"YOUR_API_KEY\",\n  domain: \"localhost\",\n  turn: true,\n  peer_id: \"media_caller\"\n}
Gateway --> UserApp : 201 Created {\n command_type: 'PEERS_CREATE',\n params:{ \n   peer_id: \"media_caller\", \n   token:\"pt-be74737d-5762-401f-a526-01fa44d98a11\"}\n }
activate Gateway 
note right of Gateway : CREATE PEER
deactivate Gateway 

Gateway <-> SkyWay_Server : SUCCESS (to bind peer id)


GET peers/media_caller/events?token=pt-be74737d-5762-401f-a526-01fa44d98a11
Gateway <-- UserApp : 200 OK {\"event\":\"OPEN\",\"params\":{peer_id:'media_caller',token:"pt-be74737d-5762-401f-a526-01fa44d98a11"}}



POST /media {"is_video":true}
Gateway <- - UserApp : 201 Created{"ip_v4":"172.16.1.106","port":50003,"media_id":"vi-985604bd-bd3e-4b33-b121-e3435842e5fc"}

POST /media {"constraints":{"audio":false}}
Gateway <- - UserApp : 201 Created{"ip_v4":"172.16.1.106", port:50004, media_id:"au-d6c4c82c-9d9c-4e12-a52a-c927ec33793e"}

POST /media/rtcp {}
Gateway <- - UserApp : 201 Created{"tcp_id":"rc-f97df2e5fd-ddad-43ef-92bb-79dd7dc1daaf","port":50003,"ip_v4":"172.16.1.106"}

POST /media/rtcp{}
Gateway <- - UserApp : 201 Created{"tcp_id":"tc-404ff658-dee5-4aac-adba-ed13abb4f92","port":50004,"ip_v4":"172.16.1.106"}




box Media Connection rgba(255,255,255,.5)
group Create connection to callee
    note over UserApp,Gateway
    
        POST /connections
        
            target_peer_id = <callee-peer-id>, // e.g., “target_callee”
            
                video_params={bandwidth:<video-band-width-in-kbps>}
                
                    audio_params={} or null
                
        
         response body contains session description protocol(SDP). This SDP should be passed on to your local RTCPeerConnection object via setRemoteDescription() method call. The same applies for answer received from remote party later in this flowchart too! So keep track carefully here onwards... :) 
        
end group
end box 


loop Loop until done sending/receiving data packets between both parties involved i.e caller & callee respectively..  
     send RTP Video To Callee's IP Address And Port Number Specified Above In Response Body Of Previous Step(i.e step number four above); Redirect It Using Local Stream Object Associated With Your Own Camera/Microphone Device(s)... Similarly Do Same For Audio Too But Use Different Ports Numbers As Shown Below Hereunder:- Send Rtp Packet Containing Encoded Voice Data Over Network Towards Other Party At Their End Point Where They Will Decode Them Back Into Original Form Before Playing Out Loud Through Speakers Or Headphones Etcetera ... Also Don't Forget About Sending Control Messages Like Receiver Reports(RR)/SenderReports(SR) Which Help Monitor Quality Levels During Call Session By Providing Feedback Information Such Jitter Buffer Size Required etc .. Finally Once Everything Is Set Up Correctly You Can Start Exchanging Real Time Multimedia Content Between Two Peers Connected Via Internet Protocol Suite Technologies Including Transmission Control Protocols(TCPIP), Hypertext Transfer Protocol(HTTP/SOAP RESTful APIs/Web Services Interfaces Based On XML JSON Formats Among Others Depending Upon Specific Requirements Needed Per Case Scenario Being Dealt Within Given Contextual Framework Under Consideration Right Now Okay?! Great Job Everyone Keep Going Strong Until Completion Reached Successfully Without Any Errors Occurring Along Way Please Thanking Very Much Indeed Cheers!!!    
     
